76561197976312757,Recommended,276770,17527448,"Posted: 13 August, 2015",all,Destyre,"I was very dubious about this game given the luke warm reception from reviews and let's play videos, not to mention the cheeky first day DLC which costs more than the game does, but eventually I caved into the nerdgasm induced by He-Man and G.I Joe armies... no homoerotic tone intended; I'm an 80's kid, had some of the toys and watched the cartoons.Anyway this is my review. I have almost 4 hours on this game at the time of reviewing so already I feel that I am in a better position to review this game than people who have 0.5 hours in it and such.First I downloaded. I was expecting Uplay but it hadn't been installed since my latest format, so I sat there for the better part of 30 minutes while it installed. Once it did I tried to login. It had been a while so I sat there thinking of the passwords I normally use but none were correct. I was then locked out of Uplay because I had tried to login too much. Not being given an option to do anything about it, and the password reset not working at all, I went onto the website to try to send a support ticket and guess what? That's right, I couldn't access the site because I was locked out. ♥♥♥♥ing hilarious right? In the end I had to call, yes, call Ubisoft and ask them to do something. The guy was helpful despite me remarking about how terrible Uplay is, he even said ""We get a lot of complaints about Uplay."" He couldn't insult the company that employed him of course, nor would I expect him to, but it was funny none the less.""Can I help you with anything else today?"" He asked. ""Yes, please tell your bosses that Uplay is a pile of♥♥♥♥♥♥and to please stop making us use it."" I laughed, he laughed and in a diplomatic tone said ""I will certainly pass that information over for you sir.""I digress. The game! So first impressions; what a crappy port! The resolution works fine of course but the menu feels quite akward, almost as if the game just had mouse support slapped in with a bit of digital tape. Still, it's not horrendous.I watched a Let's play video earlier of a guy reviewing it and he hit the roof when he saw the shop with microtransactions. Erm, mate? You can grind that money and it's really effin easy too. So scratch that as a con off of your list if you are thinking about this game. Microtransactions are purely for impatient/lazy people. They are not necessary!The framerate. Yes most people have an opinion of how choppy it feels being locked at 30fps. Well I didn't, it felt fine to me even on full graphics. I'm not going to say that people who are going on about that are snobs or anything, but it's no where near as jumpy as they make out. If it is, I would maybe suggest that it's their rigs...maybe lacking in ram or up to date drivers, I don't know. Update: Been playing for 11 hours now so far and not had a single problem with framerate. Just a bunch of snobs complaining about something which isn't even noticable then.I do have a couple of problems with the performance though: you can't alt+tab. Well you can, but if you do, the resolution will reset to default (1280x768 iirc). In this day and age, inexcusable. Also when I was doing the tutorial I was given these TINY icons on the screen telling me what key to press; so tiny that I couldn't see what it said. I'm assuming this is because the resolution was never meant to go that high on consoles and they just didn't bother to make the icons bigger to compensate... but otherwise the resolution is fine.So the gameplay. It's a tower defence game with toys. It's actually a lot of fun. The graphics are a little dated looking and the controls quite basic, but that's by no means a horrible thing. The gameplay is alot of fun. You can unlock upgrades and each army feels quite unique if not in it's options but in it's feel. Campaign seems only good if you want to unlock stuff but gets quite annoying later on. The weekly thing seems quite fun. I want to try co-op when I convince my friends to get it, but for now my experience is in single player.The controls are fine for the most part, but now and again you are given control of a map defined flying unit.... the controls are screwed for those and that needs to be fixed asap.It's a good game, despite it's shortcomings. I have read a post from a developer on another review saying how they are looking into the framerate cap, so they at least haven't given up on it. A few fixes here and there and it will be great. It's really up to you if you want to pay 25 pounds (or $30, whichever currency you use) for everything; You only really get half a game if you get the vanilla and not the hall of fame edition. It's really cheeky of them to do that but I still think this game is worth that price: providing they add some general fixes to make the game more PC friendly. The only real gripe is with Uplay. I hate it, it doesn't work well, slow, and it's just more unnecessary processing power with everything else I'm running"
