,Recommended,276770,19242249,"Posted: 23 November, 2015",all,Reverend Jesse V92,"Toy Soldiers War Chest is made by Signal Studios and published by Ubisoft; this means it uses UPlay, so if you have some kind of aversion to UPlay, be advised. The game also features a 60FPS cap because the game's physics are calculated via the frame rate.TSWC comes with 4 armies to play as by default:- Kaiser (WWI German Empire)- Phantom (Sci-Fi Space Marines)- Starbright (Fantasy Girls' Toys)- Dark Lord (DnD-esque RPG themed set)In addition, there is day-one DLC that adds up to four more armies:- GIJoe (1980s)- Cobra (1980s)- He-Man (1980s)- Assassin's CreedSignal really dropped the ball by not including Skeletor as a faction and instead including Assassin's Creed. Although I am sure the inclusion of the well-known Ubisoft franchise was purely a contractual obligation and I understand it.The game also features shortcut-micro transactions. While these optional payments may save you an hour or two of game play earning the in-game coins used to unlock turret upgrades, I cannot say it's worth it.The game play is much more solid than Signal's previous game, Toy Soldier: Cold War. Cold War is bundled with the original Toy Soldiers game in a port made by Chrome Studios; Signal had nothing to do with porting Complete to PC, so keep that in mind.Why is the game play better than TS:C? Let's start with the biggest game changer: The turret upgrades.In previous Toy Soldiers games, the turrets had only a level-1-2-3 upgrading system. In TS:WC the turrets now have three trees to upgrade: Attack, Defense, and Range. This allows the upgrades to be diversified.There are several types of turrets as well. These are based on the GIJoe army, but the turrets have the same archetypes across all 8 armies:- Anti-Infantry- Anti-Vehicle- Anti-Air- ArtilleryThe game features two different building pads, large and small. AA and artillery turrets can only be built on large pads, while anti-troop and anti-vehicle turrets can be built on any platform.The game also features a 'hero character' system which can be a game changing aspect.For instance, in the GI Joe set, after filling the kill points bar up to a certain level, you unlock the ability to play as the GI Joe character Duke, complete with screw holes and action figure joints. Duke has a few weapons, like an automatic rifle, a rocket launcher, and grenades. However, filling the bar more without using Duke will allow you to use the Dragonfly attack helicopter, which has machine guns and missile launchers. Filling the bar all the way allows you to call in a Skystriker bombing run. All the armies have their own unique hero units; Cobra has Cobra Commander and He-Man has the titular hero, and such.However, these hero units rely on batteries to use. The character and mid-tier vehicle use battery power, and the bar depletes over time. You can fill the bar by picking up the batteries scattered across the level, but these batteries are finite, leading to you being mostly dependent on your gun turrets. This is a smart move from a design perspective as the hero units can pretty much face roll all enemies on the playing field.So the turrets; at first, all the upgrades are locked. The first few levels as you first begin will be slightly challenging without the needed coins to unlock the upgrades. However, you earn a very large sum of coins in each level which can unlock one or two upgrades per-successful level completion, which means unlocking all the upgrades is just a matter of maybe an hour or two.The game measures your progress in 3 area, on a scale of bronze, silver, gold, platinum:- Aggression- Profits- Toybox healthAggression is how long you wait between waves. In order to obtain the platinum medal for aggression, you must skip the wave wait times on every wave almost instantly.Profits are how much resources/money you have leftover at the end of the level. This is also easy to get if you are frugal and don't mindlessly upgrade turrets. You can also earn more credits back by selling anti-air turrets after the final aircraft waves have finished.Toy box health is how much of the health of your base, or 'toy box' has left. In order to make platinum, the toy box MUST end the game with 100% health. In several levels, there are multiple toy boxes, which means you must cover all angles of attack.The main game's campaign does not feature the DLC armies; however, at certain points after playing through the campaign, you will unlock 'survival' levels that are based on the DLC armies. These survival levels are never-ending waves of enemies with increasing numbers. Even with a perfect defence, the turrets will take damage over time and will require repairs or they will be destroyed. It's a war of attrition, and it goes on as long as you are willing to put up a fight.- GI Joe Survival- Cobra Survival- He-Man Survival- Assassin's Creed SurvivalThe game has a randomly chosen 'Weekly War' campaign that changes each week. The war includes several levels where you fight one random army in the game and by beating the campaign you unlock coins and upgrade boxes for the turrets.The game has multiplayer listed on the store, but I haven't tried it, and as such I cannot pass judgement on the multiplayer aspect.Overall, if you like 1980s GI Joe or He-Man, and you want to have an afternoon of fun rolling in nostalgia, I'd give it a try. The upside of UPlay is that if you unlock the UPlay achievements, you earn UPlay credits which can unlock cosmetic skins for the default four armies, as well as the soundtrack and backgrounds.If you have any concerns or questions about the game you want to know before buying it, leave a comment and I will answer it and append your answer to my review."
